A long cape fitted with a hood. The elaborate stitching and symbols sewn on thick cloth give it a feeling of steadfastness, making the wearer feel at ease.
A hair accessory that lets you do your hair like a certain Echoforge employee. Women will flock to you if you wear this! (not a guarantee)

An outfit worn by a certain worker at the Echoforge that has a chic aura to it (while also looking a little gaudy). The combination of thick fabric and leather makes this a highly practical fashion option for adventurers everywhere.
A hair accessory that lets you do your hair like a certain apprentice at the Echoforge. The side-braid is particularly charming.

An outfit worn by a certain apprentice at the Echoforge that manages to look neat and pretty but also active at the same time. The lines of the skirt and work apron go together to create a serious, hard-working impression.
An outfit set centered around a cute yet elegant one piece dress. The enamel shoes are difficult to take care of, but elevate the rest of the chic, elegant outfit to the next level.

An outfit that's easy to move around in while also not lacking in places to store things, particularly in the leather belt pouches and work apron. The boots are made with soft leather, making them easy to walk around in, too.
A set of overalls made of thick denim, designed to feel extremely comfortable when you're being active.
A set of overalls made of thick denim, designed to feel extremely comfortable when you're being active.
A hat worn by a wide variety of artisans. It's both water and fire resistant, and designed to keep its wearer as safe as possible.

An outfit designed to be suitable for all kinds of work, from precise tasks to heavy manual labor. Particular attention was paid to the stitching of the shoulder portions so that they wouldn't get in the way during tasks.
An outfit carefully designed to look dependable without appearing intimidating that shows off the powerful build of the wearer underneath.
An outfit that is made with extra cloth around the cuffs and neck to make it look more elegant. It's sure to attract gazes of admiration even on formal occasions, not just when adventuring.
A cap made of a sturdy material, for farmers who want to be stylish even when they're hard at work in the fields.
An outfit set primarily made up of a setup of sturdy, easy to move around in overalls. The well-made denim material adapts well to your body, letting you enjoy working hard under the sun.
A hat made for someone by a skilled tailor and capped with the feather of a rare bird. It's even more elegant when worn with the matching outfit.
An outfit tailored for well-off youngsters that's a high-quality, highly loveable work of art. The shoes are designed to hold up even during intense movement.
A hat worn by Salamzahd's gatekeepers, designed to encourage you to sweat in order to keep cool on especially hot days.

An outfit worn by gatekeepers in Salamzahd. It's designed to feel liberating, fitting for a town where so many people come and go, but is also designed to resist the strong sunlight and sand-carrying air you find in the area.

An outfit worn by the troupe which symbolises gallantry and flamboyance in meekness. These outfits are designed by the troupe's own tailor, who sews them all individually to hold up to intense movement.
This grand, dignified outfit was once used during the troupe's performances, and is a special piece of craftsmanship designed and made painstakingly by the troupe's own tailor.
The outfit worn by workers at the Alliance Registrar. The combination of highly mobile knickerbockers and the invigorating, active impression created by the top makes the whole outfit fun to wear.
An extremely modern, fashionable outfit that really screams aesthetician. Even the belt pouches were designed to be fashionable while still being functional.
A headband worn by employees at the Fii Farm, made to look like the ears of a Fii. Wear this, and you too can feel like a Fii!
An outfit worn by employees at the Fii Farm Agency that's just adorable, and more than the sum of its plain-looking parts. The ribbons attached to the wrists and ankles draw particular attention.
A hat worn by the questmaster in Asterliese's Development Bureau. Given its small size, it's always a mystery how it doesn't fall off her head.
An outfit that is fundamentally practical, but has a dash of playfulness about it, too. The ribbon at the neck symbolizes its cute side, while the gloves create a hard-working impression.
A refreshingly blue hat worn by people who handle liquid memory which fits perfectly with the associated apron. The design projects an aura of cleanliness, making it highly popular with adventurers.

The outfit worn by memorade stand employees. The buttons down the side are particularly distinctive, while the apron (which looks like a high waist skirt) full of functionality. It manages to look both cute and intellectual at the same time.
A hat designed for the occasionally dangerous field of Echo research. It's easily spotted by its sturdy fabric and careful stitching, both of which make it suitable for adventuring, too.

An outfit designed for the occasionally dangerous field of Echo research. It's easily spotted by its sturdy fabric and careful stitching, both of which make it suitable for adventuring, too. It's highly functional too, as exemplified by the pockets and gloves.
This distinctive hat instantly tells you that someone is a asset counter supervisor. It's made of thick cloth, and protects their head as well as they protect your assets.
The simple, functional outfit worn by asset counter supervisors in Asterliese. It was designed primarily to be sturdy and so is made of thick cloth, but is also surprisingly breathable.
The small hat worn by the questmaster in Salamzahd's Development Bureau that goes really well with the associated outfit. Wear this and you too will feel like a questmaster!
One of the few things in Salamzahd, a place where even the wind is hot, that seems cool and refreshing to the eyes. The chest ribbon makes this otherwise liberating outfit look more serious.

The outfit worn by workers at Salamzahd's asset management counter. While it was made primarily to be easy to work in, great effort was put into making every little detail feel like something that belongs in the desert. It's also made using high-quality materials, and very comfortable as a result.
A pair of glasses identical to those of an apprentice at the Echoforge. Simply wearing them is enough to make you three times smarter...appearance-wise.

Based on a juice made from the fruit of magnia trees, which have long been found on the continent. The recipe has remained unchanged for many years.
A medicine of refined flux. Applying it to a weapon improves the flow of an adventurer's flux, strengthening the weapon.
Flux derived from raw ore that generates a solid curtain to cushion against impacts. A favorite of certain Bapharists who believe that one can sense the blessings of the Bapharian god within it.
A medicinal drink made with a rare component extracted from magnia trees that substantially reduces the effects of physical exertion.
A drug aimed at adventurers that both stimulates and vitalizes the eyes, allowing the user unparalleled clarity of vision on the battlefield and increasing their chances of landing critical blows.
Its ingredients contain a great deal of fire flux, promoting the circulation of bioflux in the body and improving the conversion efficiency of fire-based attacks.

Reduces ambient temperature around the user. Designed based on principles gleaned from a Bapaharian coolant, though the fundamental concepts behind the coolant's workings have not yet been fully laid bare.
Mixed with lightning flux-rich ore fragments. This flux induces an electrical breakdown effect which enhances lightning attacks.
Known for its distinctive method of manufacture, in which flux is added to soil and left to ferment for a year before extraction and use as an ingredient.

Reacts to attacks containing fire flux by generating resistance. Supposedly, there was once a person who got a little carried away and jumped directly into a fire while using it—and walked away with burns to show for it.
Formulated with oils extracted from plants typically found in the highlands. Generates a resistance to ice. Often used as protection against the cold in northern regions.
Creates a flow of flux across the surface of the skin, forming a layer that diverts electrical attacks. A standard piece of kit carried to prevent accidents in Bapharian ruins.
A substance not unlike that secreted by subterranean monsters. Reacts to soil that contains flux, and seems to be able to move through earth.

(Returned at mission completion.) Flux derived from raw ore that generates a solid curtain to cushion against impacts. A favorite of certain Bapharists who believe that one can sense the blessings of the Bapharian god within it.

(Returned at mission completion.) A drug aimed at adventurers that both stimulates and vitalizes the eyes, allowing the user unparalleled clarity of vision on the battlefield and increasing their chances of landing critical blows.
(Returned at mission completion.) Its ingredients contain a great deal of fire flux. Promotes the circulation of body's bioflux and improves the conversion efficiency of fire-aspected attacks.

(Returned at mission completion.) Reduces ambient temperature around the user. Designed based on principles gleaned from a Bapaharian coolant, though the fundamental concepts behind the coolant's workings have not yet been fully laid bare.
(Returned at mission completion.) Mixed with ore fragments that contain lightning flux. This flux induces an electrical breakdown effect which enhances lightning-aspected attacks.
(Returned at mission completion.) Known for its distinctive method of manufacture, in which flux is added to soil and left to ferment for a year before extraction and use as an ingredient.
(Returned at mission completion.) Made with a special plant which accumulates large amounts of light flux when exposed to moonlight.
(Returned at mission completion.) Originally carried by the Dracari before being taken on the battlefield. Perhaps for that reason, some adventurers in the early days steered clear of using it.

(Returned at mission completion.) Reacts to attacks containing fire flux by generating resistance. Supposedly, there was once someone who got a little carried away and jumped directly into a fire while using this—and walked away with burns to show for it.

(Returned at mission completion.) Formulated with oils extracted from plants typically found in the highlands. Generates a resistance to ice. Often used as protection against the cold in northern regions.

(Returned at mission completion.) Creates a flow of flux across the surface of the skin, forming a layer that diverts electrical attacks. A standard piece of kit carried to prevent accidents in Bapharian ruins.
(Returned at mission completion.) A substance not unlike that secreted by subterranean monsters. Reacts to soil that contains flux, and seems to be able to move through earth.
(Returned at mission completion.) Its ingredients includes a substance that refracts light, which induces a light-resistant effect. Has been known to distort the user's appearance on occasion.
(Returned at mission completion.) Thought to be the earliest invented among the varieties of starbalm. In days past, travelers would carry some as a remedy to protect them from the darkness of night.
(Returned at mission completion.) Chocolate that increases the cooldown speed of tactical, ultimate, and Echo skills. It's really just chocolate in name only, though, as it's quite bitter.

(Returned at mission completion.) Though on the extreme bitter end of chocolates, its bitterness is actually part of its appeal to a dedicated base of customers. "More bitter, more better!" or so it claims.

A type of crystal discovered in the Raycrisstal Mine. Due to its rich flux content and high Echo affinity, a mine was built to extract it.
Found in Dragon's Rive. A chunk of a massive fang which appears to have come from a Dracari. It is heavy, and feels eerily intimidating.
Ore found behind Thieves' Falls. A staple of adventurer loot hauls, it finds many a use throughout the city, although its impurities take considerable time and effort to process.
A small Bapharian part that once protected the Pillar of Divinity. It does things—amazing things!—although how it all works is a complete head-scratcher.
A particularly efficient integrated core found in the Pillar of Divinity. Somehow, they managed to pack many times the functionality into the same tiny footprint as the standard core.
A stunning gemstone that was first discovered in Steelwalker Ravine. It has since become one of the Bahamar Highlands' flagship exports and is extolled as a gift from the Bapharian god.
Part of the Bapharian legacy unearthed in the Skyspire Ruins. A complex array of parts, it's impossible to reconstruct once disassembled. As such, none have yet pinpointed its specific use.
Part of the Bapharian legacy unearthed in the Skyspire Ruins. It does not appear to have any use on its own, but could fit perfectly in place of broken parts of other Bapharian relics.

A relic of an ancient civilization found buried in the Soundless City. Developed with a closely-guarded ironworking technique to fend off foreign foes. As such, the means for its manufacture have become forever lost to time.

Ore that can be found on Sophra's Mountain Path. Shines brightly in dim places. There is a custom of following in the tradition of the great Sophra and gifting these as lucky charms to those facing hardship and trials.

An insect denizen of Halflight Hive. When it emerges, it will often build a nest to protect itself from the environment. The mucus excreted during this process is extracted and used as a coating agent to provide a unique luster and pliability.
An insect denizen of Halflight Hive. A more developed form of steelbug capable of building large, sturdy nests. A valuable—and rare—specimen.

Bough of a tree whose roots have spread into Candlemere Tomb. Despite having been found in a place without water, it is for some reason suffused with moisture throughout. Attempting to get rid of this moisture can easily result in it breaking, so care must be taken when processing it.

Sand found in great abundance in the Ruins of Borwam. The individual grains are large and heavy—one can even sort them when they're soaked in water. Its weight is notoriously close to that of gold dust, making for many a scam throughout the years, and even today.

Sand found in the Ruins of Borwam. Its grains are jagged and sharp and can cause injury if touched with bare hands. The place where it can be located is said to be one where demons dwell and result in one being unknowingly covered in blood.
An ore found in the Ballroom of the Water Faeries. Its vibrant surface blinks and flickers depending on the humidity level, leading many shocked beholders to swear it's a living, breathing being.

An ore mined in the Fallen Arsenal. Because it exudes a small amount of a rather pungent gas, the handling of this ore is seen as the duty of prisoners, and it is often called a "stone of punishment."
A piece of the Bapharian legacy found in the Chained One's Spawnery. Comprised of an unfathomable number of small parts, one has little hope of discerning how they fit together.

A piece of the Bapharian legacy found in the Chained One's Spawnery. An assembly of delicate parts that exhibit shocking amounts of power. Nonetheless, it seems that only a small fraction of its functions are still operational, and a full grasp of its workings remains enigmatic, at best.

An ore that can be found in the Ruins of Sevran's Tomb. Can be deformed when exposed to wind. When a cave can sometimes seem to give a different impression upon a visit after some time, this ore is said to be the cause.
Part of the Bapharian legacy found in the Sanctuary of Blessings. Though small, its entire surface is beautifully decorated; one can plainly see that it was produced with advanced technology.

Part of the Bapharian legacy found in the Sanctuary of Blessings. Grand adornments and advanced functionality become one in an artful, delicate balance. It would hardly seem out of place in an art museum.

An ancient weapon found in the Crused Knoll Ruins. Its broken and worn appearance speaks to the fierceness of the battles it has seen. The tenacity of true warriors has transcended time and intertwines with the flux within, faint but unmistakeable.
Sand that piled up in the Sandstone Corridors of Khartoum. Quite grainy, with an uneven, jagged texture. Broken shells and fossils are mixed into it, though their origins are unknown.

A rock found in the Abandoned Alston Mines. Quite heavy, with a blackened and scraggy surface. Contains a quantity of metals that are useful in crafting weapons, but the high degree of impurities means it takes some time to process.

A metal plate found in Byrnhald Castle Exaquary. Parts of it are weathered, and it has clearly been a great deal of time since it came loose of whatever it was a part of. The remaining portion can be used for metalwork and construction.

A metal plate found in Byrnhald Castle Exaquary. Some kind of massive impact has crushed and warped it. The material itself is still in reasonably good condition, so would make a sturdy material if reshaped.
A component stored in the Drava Royal Institute. Used as an internal component for complex ancient Bapharian artifacts. Simply constructed, and without any obvious function itself.

A component stored in the Drava Royal Institute. Part of an ancient and complex Bapharian relic, it seems to serve an important function. When exposed to a flux current, it reacts by producing light and a rumbling sound.

A fragment dropped from all kinds of enemies. It feels curious to the touch, neither organic nor metallic in nature. It can be processed in a wide variety of ways, such as cutting, crushing, and melting.

A beautiful fragment dropped from all kinds of enemies. If you listen closely, it emits a faint sound, perhaps due to its altered flux pattern. Some have even claimed to hear human voices coming from it.
Ore gathered on the Asteria Plains. Can be processed into valuable materials. It's not uncommon to find multiple types of metal within a single specimen.
A stone collected on the Asteria Plains. Adds a great deal of structural support to buildings when pulverized into fragments and mixed with other stone, and spread on walls, wood, and so forth.
A stone collected in the Asteria Plains. Can be mixed with oil to produce a number of different shades. Commonly used in painting to add a little color to everyday life.
Ore gathered in the Bahamar Highlands. Can be processed into valuable materials. it's not uncommon to find multiple types of metal within a single specimen.
Ore gathered in the Bahamar Highlands. Easily smelted into a very sticky metal. As such, it's a common component in a variety of daily necessities.
A stone collected in the Bahamar Highlands. Easy to smelt, easy to mix with other materials, and can be used to conveniently amalgamate multiple properties in one.
Ore gathered in Dragon's Rive. Can be processed into valuable materials, and it's not uncommon to find multiple types of metal within a single specimen.
A fossil collected in Dragon's Rive. Particularly discerning collectors would pay top luno for fully intact, exceptionally rare specimens.
A stone collected in Montegnor Valley. Adds a great deal of structural support to buildings when pulverized into fragments and mixed with other stone, and spread on walls, wood, and so forth.
A stone collected in Montegnor Valley. Easy to process, easy to mix with other materials, and can be used to conveniently bundle together multiple properties in one.
Sand gathered in the Erstgreen Sands. Easily smelted into a very sticky metal. As such, it's a common component in a variety of daily necessities.

An insect collected in the Erstgreen Sands. Can be found lurking in a number of places, such as in plants, dirt, and tree bark, and under rocks. It has a wide range of uses—as food, in medicines, and as scientific specimens, to name a few.
Sand gathered in the Erstgreen Sands. Easily smelted into a very sticky metal. As such, it's a common component in a variety of daily necessities.
A fossil collected in the Erstgreen Sands. Despite its peculiar shape, it's commonly processed into tools, but also often kept intact as decorations or specimens.

A fossil collected in the Erstgreen Sands. Valued as a research material for a number of reasons, not least of which the fact that it can aid in the discovery of already-extinct creatures. Some specimens even exhibit an flux reaction that cannot be reproduced in the present era.
A fossil collected in the Erstgreen Sands. Particularly discerning collectors would pay top luno for fully intact, exceptionally rare specimens.
An ore gathered on the Asteria Plains. Easily smelted into a very sticky metal. As such, it's a common component in a variety of daily necessities.
An ore gathered in the Ruins of Borwam. Easily smelted into a very sticky metal. As such, it's a common component in a variety of daily necessities.

An uncommon part from ancient times, obtained in the Chained One's Spawnery. A step above conventional parts across the board. Even its tiniest components are useful, making an intact part exceptionally valuable.
A fragment collected in Soundless City. Particularly discerning collectors would pay top luno for fully intact, exceptionally rare specimens.
Ore gathered in Steelwalker Ravine. Can be processed into valuable materials, and it's not uncommon to find multiple types of metal within a single specimen.

A Bapharian relic that can be found the Sunlit Timberpath. Manufactured under exacting specifications to fit perfectly where it is needed. It fits so well that one can sense the beauty of its form: perfect, flawless, and without deviation.

A mineral that can be found in Torchlight Thickets. There are many deductions as to its origins, including it being transformed volcanic ash or carried by water and winds, but the truth remains unknown. Awaiting future research.
A Bapharian relic that can be collected in Everfall Forest. Shaped like a board, and touching the center causes it to emit light. Research as to its function is still ongoing.

An uncommon part from ancient times, obtained in Windsprite's Rostrum. A step above conventional parts across the board. Even its tiniest components are useful, making an intact part exceptionally valuable.

A piece of the Bapharian legacy that can be collected in Roseblush Woods. A round, wheel-like contraption. It rotates far more smoothly than a modern equivalent even with the same force applied, and it makes little sound.
A plant collected on the Asteria Plains. The inside is hollow, so it's often used as a kind of natural pipe. Thicker, stouter plants can even be reinforced and take the place of pillars and walls.
A plant collected on the Asteria Plains. When processed, it can be made into an extremely durable fiber. In constant demand as a prime material for cloth and rope.
A flower collected on the Asteria Plains. Has a delicate, graceful sort of beauty. Primarily used for ornamentation and medicinal purposes, but also makes a pleasant tea if sundried and steeped.
A plant collected in the Bahamar Highlands. Its secretions repel insects, so when burned, its smoke serves as a natural repellent. Also commonly laid out as bedding for livestock.

A fruit collected in the Bahamar Highlands. Has a potent scent, and can be dried and sprinkled to serve as a deodorizer. One can enjoy its scent when nibbled on raw, but be warned that its strong bitterness is an acquired taste.
A branch collected in the Bahamar Highlands. Younger specimens tend to be more flexible, and grow stiffer with the passage of time. Ones with desirable shapes are often used in gardening.
A flower collected in Montegnor Valley. Grows in a variety of colors. A large, beautiful flower with many petals, it's a prime choice as the focal flower in bouquets.
A flower collected in Montegnor Valley. Known for its pleasant fragrance. Commonly used in potpourri and perfumes.
A flower collected in Montegnor Valley. Known for its pleasant fragrance. Commonly used in potpourri and perfumes.
A herb that can be collected in Erstgreen Sands. When processed, it can be made into an extremely durable fiber. Makes a great material for making cloth and rope, and is in constant demand.
A branch collected in Erstgrene Sands. Favored for use in gardening and as a holder for other tools. Light and easy to handle, one can often see children swinging them around in play fights.
An insect collected in Erstgrene Sands. It feeds on sap and moss found on the ground. Characterized by its glossy shell, it's sometimes bred by resourceful entomologists.
A plant collected in Dragon's Rive. The inside is hollow, so it's often used as a kind of natural pipe. Thicker, stouter plants can even be reinforced and take the place of pillars and walls.
A plant collected in Dragon's Rive. It is said that, even should one be stepped on with considerable force, it will rise back up the following day—the very symbol of indomitable will.
An herb that can be collected in the Soundless City. When processed, it can be made into an extremely durable fiber. In constant demand as a prime material for cloth and rope.

A plant that can be collected in Dragon's Rive. The inside is hollow, so it's often used as a kind of natural pipe. Thicker, stouter ones can even be reinforced and take the place of pillars and walls.

Driftwood collected in the Bahamar Highlands.
Its surface has been washed smooth by flowing water. Its unique shape and natural curve make it an attractive component in a variety of handicrafts.
An aquatic plant that can be collected on the Asteria Plains.An exceptionally useful material that can store a great deal of water and nutrients. However, extracting it takes considerable toil.

Driftwood collected in Montegnor Valley.
Its surface has been washed smooth by flowing water. Its unique shape and natural curve makes it an attractive component in a variety of handicrafts.

A aquatic plant collected in Montegnor Valley.
Its secretions repel insects, so when burned, its smoke serves as a natural repellent. Also commonly laid out as bedding for livestock.
An aquatic plant collected in Montegnor Valley. A water- and nutrient-rich material of exceptional utility, the extraction of which takes considerable toil.

A crystal replete with flux. They are easy to collect and process, and used regularly in adventurers' crafting projects. They incorporate flux from the air and underground during crystallization, so composition and shape vary depending on the region.

A clay paste that has been specially treated for us in a spheromutator. Different formulations come in a variety of colors. A first-rate good that can only be created by master craftspeople.

An ore that can be found in a variety of places. Brittle as-is, but if its flux is brought into balance, it becomes remarkably solid.
A fossil that can be found in a variety of places. Possesses a peculiar shape and is not only made into tools, but often kept as-is to be admired or preserved.
A plant that can be found in a variety of places. Grows quickly and prolifically. Has been appreciated for many years due to how easily it can be obtained in times of trouble.

A seed that can be found in many places. It has an peculiar—and unpleasant—scent and is often eaten by wild animals. It gets sticky when ground up, and can be used for a variety of adhesive applications.

A mineral that can be found in many places. Exposure to wind and rain has rendered the surface perfectly smooth and beautiful to behold. With further polishing, it can be processed into a number of useful tools, and even the occasional work of art.
A mineral that can be found in many places..The components that comprise this rock are able to improve soil quality and drainage, and so it is often used on farmland to maintain soil condition.

A bean that can be found in the Erstgreen Sands It has an peculiar—and unpleasant—scent and is often eaten by wild animals. It gets sticky when ground up, and can be used for a variety of adhesive applications.

My name's Kors, and I'm a fairly experienced adventurer and Blade Warden. This is a class that requires a lot of knowledge to master in order to both better hold the front lines in battle and support your party. My experience will allow me to teach you a lot if you're interested, so what do you say to accompanying me on a quest? The more skilled Blade Wardens out there to help us out, the better!

Hey! It's Kors the Blade Warden again. I'm hearing that some deadly monsters have been popping up in Minsterhorn—and not the fluffy, harmless kind, either. They've been actively targeting people and livestock. The people there want to enlist the help of a Blade Warden in tackling the problem, since we're skilled at fighting while protecting things. I'm planning to go, but it'd sure be reassuring if you had my back, too. What do you say?

Hey! It's Kors the Blade Warden again. You up for giving me a hand with something again? I've taken on a job to deliver some heyhelm beans—which sounds simple enough, but it sounds like there's a part two after that's done that'll require another pair of helping hands. I don't think it'll involve any fighting, but I'd still feel a lot better if I had you with me. Thanks!

Hey! It's Kors the Blade Warden again. This one's still a bit of an enigma, but it sounds like something weird is going on near Rietz. I've been asked to see if there's any truth to the rumors—and if something is going on, put an end to it. You couldn't give me a hand, could you? I'm planning to go there regardless, but I could really use your help.

It's Kors the Blade Warden again. Remember how I asked if you could give me a hand if something happened near Rietz? Well, it did. A really strong monster has shown up—and it sounds like it's one I have a personal connection with. Can you help me? I'm begging you! I don't think I can do this without your help.

My name's Manuel! I'm just an ordinary Twin Striker now, but I'm going to go down as a hero one day: count on it! You're a Twin Striker too, right? Then come help me defeat <value type="enemyName" id="[CQ102_001_enemy1]"/>! A friend of mine was going to come with me, but he collapsed with stomach pain, so now I'm on my own... He's a Twin Striker too, so I think it'd be easier if someone of the same class took his place. So c'mon! We can get stronger together!

It's Manuel the budding Twin Striker hero again! I'm working on a request to defeat 
<value type="enemyName" id="[CQ102_002_enemy1]"/>, and it'd really help if you'd come with me. I wanna introduce you to my friend this time, too! You're like the hero we dream of being, and I want him to see that, too! C'mon, let me boast about my good fortune in meeting you! Please!

It's Manuel the budding Twin Striker hero again! You ever heard of Vortex Strike? It's a skill that was used by the legendary Twin Striker Ahim. Doesn't that just sound awesome? I wanna learn how to use it, too! The search will go twice as fast if you help, too, so please! Give me a hand!

It's Manuel the budding Twin Striker hero again! I'm making good progress on learning how to use Vortex Strike, but I feel like I need one more clue on how to master it. That's why I'm planning to go on a tour of places related to heroes. I guess you could call it a pilgrimage of sorts. Maybe I'll find the knowledge I seek during it. So let's do this thing!

Manuel the budding Twin Striker hero again! You know how the great hero Ahim once defeated a Quad Arm? I've been dying to do the same one day! I found a <value type="enemyName" id="[CQ102_005_enemy1]"/>, too, but something doesn't seem right about it. If we leave it unattended, I'm honestly afraid it's going to attack Rietz. For the good of Rietz, I need your help in defeating it!

Hello! My name's Lily, and I'm a Keen Strider. Are you interested in being a Keen Strider? You are, aren't you? It's written all over your face! We should work on becoming better at this class together! ...and while we're at it, it would really help if you'd give me a hand with this job I took on. We Keen Striders have to stick together! Right?

Hello! It's Lily the Keen Strider again! I still can't believe how fast you were able to grasp the fundamentals of archery...you're a real natural at this class! With a bit more practice, you'll be fighting like the best of us! Speaking of which, I took on another job defeating <value type="enemyName" id="[CQ103_002_enemy1]"/> in the hopes that the practice would help me grow stronger. How about we try going it together? Come on, you know you want to!

Hello! It's Lily the Keen Strider again! I hope your archery practice is going well! Not unrelated to that, there's actually something I've been wanting to try for a while now, and I'd like you to join me. Specifically, I want to try fighting aerial enemies! That's where we Keen Striders really shine, you see, since we can actually hit them, while other classes often struggle against them. You never know when you'll have to fight against some yourself, so why not practice now so you don't panic when that moment comes?

Hello! It's Lily the Keen Strider again! I finally found what I've been looking for: the Sky Serpent! Someone who made the journey over from Rietz happened to spot him on the way. The sighting wasn't long ago either, so I'm sure he's still there. Please help me: this is my chance to finally avenge my brother, and I can't do it alone!

Hello! It's Lily the Keen Strider again! After searching for so long, I finally found <value type="enemyName" id="[CQ103_005_enemy1]"/>! Their nest is in <value type="locationName" id="[CQ103_005_area1]"/>! If we attack them there, there's no way they'll run away. I'm ready to settle this once and for all—but I can't do it alone. Please, lend me a hand!

My name is...what was it again? Ah, that's right, it's Sara. I have a favor to ask, you see. I need to defeat some <value type="enemyName" id="[CQ104_001_enemy1]"/>, but for reasons I will not get into to, I'm not able to do so myself. I really need the task to be done, though... I don't suppose I could count on your help, could I?

Hello, it's the being they call the Spell Weaver Sara again with yet another request... What a mouthful. This time, I require ore from the Asteria Plains, and flux from <value type="enemyName" id="[CQ104_002_enemy1]"/>. The former can be acquired through peaceful means, but the latter will certainly require combat. Neither are negotiable for my purposes, though, which is why I come to you for aid. Might you help me once more?

Hello, it's the being they call the Spell Weaver Sara again—or the Echo possessing her body, at least. You didn't think my introduction could get any more complicated, did you? Regardless, I would like to request your help once more in returning this body to her and putting this situation right. This time, I wish to extract flux from the grave of a great person who once walked this world—a shared ancestor of we Spell Weavers, if we will. Perhaps that might capture your interest.

Hello, it's the Echo possessing the body of the Spell Weaver Sara again. I really need to think of a shorter way to introduce myself... Regardless, my latest task is to collect my own bioflux. To that end, I have learned the location of several tools I once used when I lived, but unfortunately all are in areas now inhabited by monsters. That's why I would truly appreciate your help again. Can I count on it?

It's me, Slaft, the Echo who once used the name of Sara. You have helped me so much in gathering flux, and I truly appreciate it. The preparations to return her body are almost complete—and not a moment too soon, as I have stopped hearing her voice. At this rate, it is only a matter of time before her consciousness disappears. This is the final favor I will ask of you: please, grant me your aid.

Hey there! The name's Marietta. You're a Foe Breaker too, right? Isn't it awesome just pulverising baddies in one blow? I've been doing this for a while, so I bet there's a ton I could teach a rookie like you about our weapon. Let's go break some <value type="enemyName" id="[CQ105_001_enemy1]"/>s together! The best teacher's always combat experience if you ask me.

Hey there! It's your buddy Marietta again. Hope your Foe Breaker training's going well. Listen, you up for helping me with a job? All it involves is defeating <value type="enemyName" id="[CQ105_002_enemy1]"/> in <value type="locationName" id="[CQ105_002_area1]"/>. I wouldn't ask normally, but my master asked me how to learn how to better work with other people...and that's not something you can do on your own, is it? I think you'd learn a lot from the experience, too. So what do you say?

Hey there! It's your buddy Marietta again. I'm planning to head out to search for my master soon, but I caught wind for something else I wanna take care of first. Sounds like one of the kids of Minsterhorn left for <value type="locationName" id="[CQ105_003_area1]"/> and hasn't been seen since, y'see... I owe a lot to the people there and would hate anything to happen to one of them, so I wanna go search. You'll help me, right?

Hey there! It's your buddy Marietta again. I went to Lallipar in search of my master, but ended up stumbling onto yet more trouble. It sounds like their food supplies and baggage was messed up by something or someone. The whole situation seems kinda familiar, too, which has kept it on my mind. I'm planning to go investigate: could I persuade you to come with me?

Hey there! It's your buddy Marietta again. You remember the whole mess in Lallipar? You know, the one that turned out to be the work of a pack of geo foxen? Well, it sounds like the same thing's happened all over again! This time, the pack was led by a Sapphire Stampede. That makes it personal: I lost to that thing once before! But I'm not gonna lose this time! So c'mon, let's go get him!

The name's Curran. You're the newie Blitz Lancer, right? I've been training in this class for a lot longer than you have now, so I'm thinking there's a thing or two I can teach you that'll be worth your while. I had someone to teach me when I was just starting out too, so I just wanna pass down the love, I guess. How about we start with how to defeat monsters? Nothing helps you get stronger fast than a real battle or two!

Hey! It's Curran the Blitz Lancer again. How's your training going? I hope it's going well, but either way, I've got some more things to teach you! This time, it's about more than just fighting, 'cause I know just doing that will get boring after a while. That's what I found, at least! I took on the perfect job at the bureau, so let's go do it together so you can get some practice in! It's the job of a teacher to make sure their pupil doesn't get bored, after all.

Hey! It's Curran the Blitz Lancer again. I hate to come to you with this...but you couldn't give me a hand, could you? See, I stupidly ended up taking on two jobs at the same time, and while both the combat one and the gathering one are simple on their own, both at the same time is turning out to be more than I can handle! Please, you've gotta help me!

Hey! It's Curran the Blitz Lancer again. You remember the story about how my old teacher is looking for a lance called the Zenithcrest? Well, I stumbled on a merchant who says they've heard of the thing! I really want to try finding it before they do—I figure it'd be a really big growth opportunity for me. Do you want to give me a hand? I'd really like to talk to you ait!

Hey! It's Curran the Blitz Lancer again. I've heard that an Ogre showed up in the Montegnor Valley, and can't stop thinking about it. That's near to where the adventurer who owned the Zenithcrest was last seen, you see. It sounds like the Ogre showed up very recently, too. I wouldn't be surprised if Rugel hadn't heard about it yet. You're up for continuing our search for the Zenithcrest, right?

I woke up to find myself in a completely unfamiliar place, unable to remember anything but my own name. There, I met a demi-human girl called Feste who seemed to take a liking to me after I saved her from a goblin, which is nice. Soon after she started calling me her lackey, though, which isn't so nice... She then told me that the ruin where I met her was a recently found one, and there may still be clues to help find my lost memories there.
It sounds like becoming an Adventurer is going to be to my benefit going forward, so let's blitz through that exam and put my name in their books!

I'm an Adventurer now! This profession will take me all around the world taking on jobs, meeting new people, and visiting new places, which is bound to help in recovering my lost memories. First I should start with the 'job that pays really well' that Jake mentioned. Just what could it entail?

At Dragon's Rive, we encountered an Aberration—a beast of legend. After the battle, a enigmatic boy by the name of Melroth descended from the sky, and used an unfamiliar word—'Visitant.' Could this word be the key to unlocking some of my lost memories? I wanted to look into the matter right away, but Feste is determined that we're going to the Two-Faced Coin next, because Jake convinced her that the owner is going to give her free food...

We learned a little more about Visitants from a priest of the Bapharian Church called Walken and his student Mirleen. Apparently these 'Visitants' came from afar and had special powers. If we want to learn more, we're going to have to make our way to the Pillar of Divinity in the Bahamar Highlands, the most sacred site in the Bapharian faith.

At the Pillar of Divinity, we met Aeryn and Tyris, two girls from 1000 years in the future. They claimed to have come to banish Aberrations before they could destroy civilization in the future, and we were eventually roped into helping them. Now it looks like Tyris has another favor to ask of me.
The flux abnormality that the omnistrobe picked up is likely to be an Aberration. Let's help Aeryn and Tyris take it down!
The Coinkeep asked us to deliver something for him. Sounds simple enough, but apparently 'once you know how this tastes, you'll never be the same again'. That's ominous...

After talking with a stray cat for a while, Feste suddenly demanded I go and bring back the meat of a Horned Goat.
I guess I should be a good servant and do as I'm told...
All we'll have to do is deliver a letter to a priest in Minsterhorn. Sounds simple enough, yet it would involve learning one of Jake's secrets.
The Coinkeep entrusted us with a job he was apparently going to give to someone else. This seems like a dangerous one...

Tyris suddenly started asking questions to a complete stranger.
I wonder if she learned something useful from it?
She looked panicked, but resolute.

Aeryn and Tyris are having an interesting discussion.
Perhaps if I can join in, I can learn more about this enigmatic duo from the future.

An insufferable rich snob came to us with a job.
Apparently they want to give the oracle something rare and valuable that will capture her interest.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Perrine told me I passed, which means I'm all done with my tasks. Henri came along while she was telling me and they got into a bit of a spat, but that's beside the point. I passed! Now I can register as an adventurer. I should report to Millie.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We found a powerful monster deep in Dragon's Rive, and just about managed to defeat it. According to Feste, it was an Aberration—a being that is not bound by space and time. But they are supposed to only exist in legend, not really exist...and considering I was able to defeat it, just what does that make me?

Jake set off for the Development Bureau ahead of us, noting that he needed to sound the alarm about the Aberration. Just then, a mysterious boy came down from the sky. He introduced himself as Melroth, and among his cryptic musings was the word 'Visitant.' Could that be a key to unlocking my memories? Supposedly it rang a bell for Feste, but she couldn't remember where she had heard it, either. Regardless, our next move should be to return to the Development Bureau and collect our reward from Jake.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We saved Walken from peril in the Skyspire Ruins. After we asked him about Visitants, he seemed more than happy to share all of his theories about them. His belief was that Visitants were outsiders with special powers, who some believed were bringers of disaster. After espousing the theory that the Church's founder was also a Visitant from another world, he was sidelined in the Church. He also passionately informed us that if we wanted to learn more, we should look in the Pillar of Divinity, the most sacred site in Bapharism. Either way, we should probably return to Minsterhorn and tell Mirleen that we were able to rescue him.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We found an Aberration sealed away on the top floor of the Pillar of Divinity. But when we approached it, a sphere of light appeared out of nowhere, and two young women descended from it. Just then, the Aberration suddenly broke free of its seal and made to attack them. In the end, we managed to defeat it, but we were none the wiser just who they were—and they were behaving very cautiously towards us. Just then, a mysterious assailant burst into the room. It was Voldigen, the almighty King of the Dracari. He overwhelmed the Aberration, making its power his own, and swatted away the gatekeeper like a mere fly. He then turned his eyes on us, and drew closer and closer... We had nowhere to flee—we were going to have to fight him. But just as we had resolved to fight an unwinnable battle, the young women nearby created a sphere of light, and told us to jump into it. We did what they said. We felt as though we were floating, the light disappeared...and the next thing we knew, we were back in the room as it was earlier. The Aberration was still sealed above us, and Voldigen was nowhere to be seen. It was if none of what we had witnessed had happened.

The two women finally explained the situation to us. Their names were Tyris and Aeryn, and we had escaped from Voldigen by traveling through time in a process called timeleaping. We were having a hard time believing their story, but when we went to leave the Pillar of Divinity, we saw our own past selves with our own eyes, lending a lot of credibility to what they were saying. Aeryn seemed to be in a lot of pain, too, perhaps due to us timeleaping. We decided to return to Lallipar in order to let her rest.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I have the part that Tyris asked for!
Now I just need to give it to her.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

The omnistrobe reaction was an Aberration after all. We defeated it, and Aeryn performed the banishment ritual. During it, the defeated Aberration was surrounded by light and guided out of existence by her. Apparently, Aberrations are paradoxical existences created when someone kills their past self, and Aeryn has the unique power to mend such distortions in causality. However, doing so exhausts her greatly. We decided to return to Rietz to let her rest.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

After returning from the Cliffside Ruin and greeting Jake, he introduced us to the Development Bureau's questmaster, Millie. She quickly discovered that the Echo we had found in the ruin was a goblin's Combat Echo. Apparently it isn't an especially rare kind of Echo, but it should prove useful to us all the same. We learned that budding adventurers have to pass a number of exams, which Millie herself will oversee. If we want to learn more, we'll have to speak to her again.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

My examinations passed, I was now a full fledged adventurer. Now I can take on requests at the Development Bureau! Millie warned me that I should never forget to raise my Adventurer Rank. A higher rank proves an adventurer's abilities, letting them get greater rewards and go into more dangerous places. You have to clear an Adventure Board to rank up, so Millie gave me my first one. She also gave me some Glory Chips (GC) for defeating that ogre at the Raycrisstal Mine, which I should be able to trade for something nice at the exchange counter. Jake told me he'd introduce me to a particularly well-paying job once I was an adventurer, so I think I'll go talk to him when I report back to the Bureau.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We received our reward from Jake, as well as some curious information. Apparently there have been numerous sightings of mysterious monsters all across the land, and there are rumors that they may be Aberrations. Furthermore, the number of such sightings increased dramatically at the same time that the Dracari started causing trouble. Jake told us he would keep an ear out for any other similar information. He also told us that the Coinkeep wants to celebrate us finishing the job! The second Feste heard this, her heart was set on hurrying to the Two-Faced Coin at once.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

No sooner had Walken and Mirleen been reunited, they launched into a fierce debate about ancient civilizations and the Skyspire Ruins. It was clear we weren't going to be able to get anything more out of either of them: all we could do was make for the Pillar of Divinity and try to learn more about Visitants there on our own.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We learned that Aeryn and Tyris came from 1000 years in the future, with the goal of banishing Aberrations. They told us that Aberrations distort space and time just by existing, and that those distortions would eventually go on to destroy the world. However, they learned that they could address the issue by banishing the Aberrations before they got too large. That, it seems, is what led them to travel back in time. However, time travel is a highly confidential matter, and so they delivered us an ultimatum: cooperate with them in their mission, or die. Both for our sakes and for the planet's, we had no choice but to help them. They bowed their heads in response to our answer, presumably regretful about the position they put us in. So now we're part of their mission to save the world—and Tyris is Feste's latest "lackey" after being tricked by her.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Tyris spoke to Aeryn while she worked on repairing the omnistrobe. From their conversation, I learned that people who time traveled to a time period were once called Visitants by the people of that time period. It seems Aeryn can sense Visitants by fluctuations in their flux—but strangely, she couldn't sense any such fluctuations in mine. Could Melroth have been wrong about me? After fixing and activating the omnistrobe, it detected a strange reading in Montegnor Valley. After handing me an omnistrobe handset for contacting them, and informing us that they would head on ahead and survey the area as they did, Aeryn and Tyris left.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Tyris thanked us for our help in banishing the Aberration and once again apologized for all that had happened. It can't have been easy on her. If the future is to be saved, Aeryn needs to banish the Aberrations. That would be difficult enough a task even without Voldigen standing in our way... According to Tyris, Voldigen himself is also an Aberration, and can absorb the power of other Aberrations to increase his own. If we don't banish them all before he gets to them, he will end up destroying the world in their place. After learning all of this, we promised once more to aid them in saving the world.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I should go and say hi to this inn's owner first.
He'll be behind the counter on the first floor.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Feste seems to be well acquainted with the owner, who people usually refer to as the Coinkeep. She seems to have built up quite a tab here, too... The Coinkeep warned me not to step outside of the city unprepared.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Supposedly this city's name is Asterliese, and it's the largest trading hub on the continent of Magna. I was floored by just how big it is—filled with buildings and people. First I should make my way to the square in front of the city gate.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

There's a giant teleportal in the square that I can warp back to from anywhere else in the world as long as I've registered myself with it. I should do that right away.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I've registered myself with the teleportal! That means I'm finally ready to head out of the city in search of clues to my lost memories. Onwards!

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Outside the city, I found myself in the vast Asteria Plains, which extended as far as the eye could see. The plains were covered with plants, ore, and Bapharian ruins—as well as, unfortunately, monsters. I'll need to be careful of those. First we should make our way to the ruin where I first met Feste. Maybe we'll find a clue to recovering my lost memories there.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We fought a group of goblins in the Cliffside Ruins, and I learned that some monsters fight together as groups—something I'll need to keep in the back of my mind. We're almost at the area where Feste found me... I wonder if we'll find anything there?

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

In the area where I awoke, we found an Echo—the result of the will of a living creature and flux combining and crystalizing. It's filled with all kinds of power, but unfortunately doesn't seem like it will help with finding my memories. Just as we went to leave, I heard a strange voice—but couldn't find its source anywhere. Outside, we met an adventurer who called himself Jake. He seems very personable, but apparently he's a well known adventurer in the city who helps keep the city's adventurers together. He offered to put in a good word for me if I want to become an adventurer—a path Feste also recommended, insisting that "looking into my missing memories can wait until we have money." I suppose she's not wrong... Either way, my next move is to go to the Bureau in Asterliese and speak to Jake.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Apparently I need to complete some tasks in order to become an adventurer. The first of these involves defeating some Geo Foxen. They don't seem like tough foes, but I'd best be ready before facing them regardless.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I defeated the Geo Foxen. I'd best tell Millie the good news!

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

The next task is to make my way through the Raycrisstal Mine, which can be accessed from the Skyquake Fields. Though monsters have taken to living there since it was sealed off, it's supposedly not too dangerous. I just have to reach the end of the Mine to complete my task!

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I can enter Raycrisstal Mine through a flux rift. These rifts are supposedly scattered all over the land, and lead into caves, ruins, and all sorts of other places. If I find any more, I should try and remember their locations.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

No one ever told us that a ferocious ogre was going to show up in the Raycrisstal Mine. Feste insists that this task was way too dangerous to be giving a budding adventurer, but nevertheless, we managed to defeat it. We should be able to move on to the next stage of our test now.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Apparently, the Development Bureau was just as surprised about the ogre appearing in Raycrisstal Mine as we were! Millie reported our findings and thanked us for taking care of it, but the test is still on. We've got more to do! Our next task is to learn about crafting, so let's start with making a weapon. Let's go talk to Henri in Artisan's Forum to find out more.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Henri told us everything we needed to know about weapon crafting: You need a formula and all the necessary materials, then you put it all together in the Spheromutator and voila! You have a weapon. My test isn't over until I make a weapon for real though, so I need to gather some materials to make an Adventurer's weapon at the spheromutator.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I crafted an Adventurer's weapon! I should go check in with Henri now.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I've finished the third task without a hitch. My last task is to craft an Augment Echo. It looks like Perrine in the Echoforge is in charge of this one. It's right across from the Development Bureau, so I should talk with her right away!

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Perrine told me what I needed to know about this task. Augment Echoes are Echoes you can equip that enhance your body's potential. They're just as important to an adventurer as a weapon! You need a formula and the materials to craft an Augment Echo. My task is to craft an Ickle Widdle Boarlet. Once I've got the materials, I'll ask the fine folks at the Echoforge to help me craft it.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I crafted an ickle widdle boarlet! I'd better talk to Perrine now.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I signed on to go and defeat a monster with Jake. Supposedly it resembles a boar and can be found at Dragon's Rive, and is stronger and more dangerous than most other monsters. As a result, we'll get paid well if we can defeat it. When I'm ready, I should go and meet Jake in front of Dragon's Rive.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I met Jake in front of Dragon's Rive. Now the three of us can head inside and defeat that monster!

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We learned that the story about the Coinkeep wanting to celebrate was just a ruse Jake thought up to mess with Feste. Once she had calmed down about this, she brought up the 'Visitant' word that Melroth had used. The Coinkeep suggested it may relate to Bapharism somehow, but claimed to know nothing else about it. Fortunately, there is a giant temple in Asterliese, so we decided to make our way there to ask around.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

In the end, we were just told off by the priest for even speaking the word Visitants, and didn't learn anything of use from him. However, a girl who had been watching us from the shadows of a pillar told us that we would learn something of use if we went to Minsterhorn. We only took our eyes off her for a moment and she had disappeared. Well, we've got no other clues to go on in learning about my memories OR Visitants... it can't hurt to do what she suggests.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

In Minsterhorn, we met a young woman by the name of Mirleen, who told us that her teacher Walken is an authority on Visitants. However, it seems he went off to visit the Skyspire Ruins and hasn't been seen since. Worried about him, she asked us to bring him back safely—and we accepted her request. Let's head over to the Skyspire Ruins and see if we can find him.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

The Pillar of Divinity is the most sacred of all sanctums in the Bapharist faith. Unfortunately, that means we won't be able to enter it without a permit... Feste tried buttering up the guard, but it was no use. Next, we need to put our heads together in Lallipar and see if we can think of a way to get one.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

In Lallipar, we learned that a group of Bapharist pilgrims were currently in the area. Supposedly they are in the ruined village of Bergmahl to pray for its people, who were wiped out by a strange monster. Particularly of interest to us was the fact that there are supposedly people of high rank in the group, including a pontifex and the Oracle herself. Perhaps we could acquire a permit to the Pillar of Divinity from them! It's worth a try.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

In Bergmahl, we ran into the enigmatic girl we had previously met in the temple in Asterliese again. After telling her that we wanted to enter the Pillar of Divinity, she shocked us by giving us a permit to get inside. Just who is she? Unfortunately she ran off before we could ask her. Still, we got what we came for. Now all we can do is try showing this to the gatekeeper.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

The gatekeeper couldn't hide his surprise when I showed him the permit I received from that pilgrim. Seemingly it truly was a genuine one. Though initially reluctant, he eventually allowed us to pass. Now we can finally enter the Pillar of Divinity! I can only hope some kind of clue to what Visitants are us waiting for us on the top floor.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Tyris and Aeryn possess a device called an omnistrobe which can be used to find Aberrations. Unfortunately, however, it was damaged in the battle at the Pillar of Divinity. They asked me to help find the part to fix it, which can be acquired in Steelwalker Ravine.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I received a message from Tyris and Aeryn to my omnistrobe handset. It seems that they can be used to transit not only your voice, but text, too. Technology really is amazing. Tyris is the only bodyguard that Aeryn has, and she is taking that duty very seriously. Meanwhile, Aeryn is feeling very apologetic for getting Feste and I involved in their trouble. I should probably go easy on the two of them until they get comfortable here.

They've set off for the village of Rietz in the Montegnor Valley. I should make my way over there and join them.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Upon our arrival in Rietz, we encountered a group of Bapharist pilgrims, and among them was the girl who gave us the permit to enter the Pillar of Divinity. It turned out she was none other than the Oracle Elenyne. Unfortunately, she left before we could call out to her, leaving us none the wiser why she had helped us. The Dracari's aggression and increase in the number of monsters were filling Magna's people with unease, and Aberrations would only serve to exacerbate that.

The next Aberration in need of release lurks in the Soundless City, a place under the purview of the Bapharian Church. Given the relative lack of adventurers coming and going through the place, Feste is quite eager—fewer adventurers means more treasure, after all. The world may be in danger, but money still keeps it spinning for her, I suppose.
Our next Aberrant target will be found among the desert sands. The highway into the desert has a checkpoint set up, so we'll need to pass through it to proceed.
The Erstgreen Sands lie ahead—and with them, new adventure. The omnistrobe is pointing us towards the desert, but we'll head for the city of Salamzahd first.

Seeking any information we could get on Aberrations, we made our way to the Bapharian temple in Salamzahd. With the aurora winds blowing, omnistrobes won't do us any good right now. Aeryn thought that the temple was a good place to turn, so we'll have to see...

We met the songstress Charlotte at the border of the desert. It seems as though her troupe, Girouette, is about to begin a performance. Both Aeryn and Elenyne want to watch, and we did promise Charlotte, so we're all going to go and have a look.
Calvain and Charlotte have are hiding away now. Separate from that, Elenyne seems to have a request—one that seems difficult to discuss in the temple.

We met back up with Aeryn and Tyris, and discussed everything that had happened with Calvain, Charlotte, Elenyne, and Jorg. Aeryn and Tyris seemed to have something on their minds, though—apparently, they're at a loss for how to talk about a particular old man.
Electra seems to need a favor. Could it have anything to do with the Bapharian Church?

After crossing the scorching desert, we finally arrived at Salamzahd Oasis. And what better way to alleviate the fatigue of a long journey than with some sweets? Tyris has decided to treat Aeryn to some cake.
Tyris says that she has something she needs to take care of personally. Feste had a hunch that something interesting was going to happen, so we've decided to follow her.

Jorg is in trouble. When he was running from the insects, he lost a piece of paper that he had put in his notebook. It just had some minor details written on it from his personal journal, or so he says...
Electra has oddly altered her request. "I want to look for the Bapharists who've gone missing." It seems as though we may learn something new about her...
Vice Commander Veronica of the Knights of Byrnhald... Will she ever know the feelings that hide in my heart...?
The omnistrobe is detecting an Aberration! But it doesn't seem to be one of the targets for release. Should we defeat it or ignore it... What will Tyris decide?
Aeryn and Tyris visit Asterliese for the first time. Each and every sight they laid eyes open was fresh and new to them, and they enjoyed a brief respite.

Salamzahd: Go to the tavern counter
Salamzahd: Go to the pavilion tavern

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

The Aberration in the Soundless City has been defeated. Upon our arrival, there was a young man fighting the beast alone. He put up a valiant fight and collapsed from exhaustion. I've decided to carry the warrior to a safe place to rest while Aeryn handles the Rite of Release. The Bapharian Templar camp ought to be nearby, so we'll make our way there.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We slew the Aberration in Halflight Hive, yet another of the creatures that need to be released. Aeryn stepped up to perform the Rite of Release, but at that moment, the creature rose again with a terrifying vigor. Suddenly, a figure descended from overhead, and laid the Aberration low with one blow from their lance. Our benefactor was Dunkirk, commander of the Knights of Byrnhald. He and a subordinate had evidently been investigating the ruins. After their departure, Aeryn was able to release the Aberration without issue. Our next move should be to return to Elenyne and inform her of our success so she doesn't worry. As we made our journey back, Tyris seemed to have something on her mind, and was lagging behind. What could it be?

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Charlotte returned to her troupe. Calvain planned to regroup with his friend, and left. So much has happened, and I could use a rest. Let's head to the public lodge and recharge for a little while.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Jorg was the son of Knight Commander Dunkirk of Byrnhald. Childhood friends with both Elenyne and Calvain, he still seems to maintain a close bond with them today. Jorg has something he wants to investigate personally, and is being assisted by his friends. However, they avoided sharing any particulars. It could be something the doesn't want people to know about. Elenyne's errand is finished, and Jorg will be remaining here, so he asked us to take Elenyne to Salamzahd.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

The mysterious old man relates an old tale about a priest. There was a woman who greatly admired this priest. The woman supposedly spoke the worlds, "In the name of Alecia." This priest searched for a sandwind flower that the woman sought. In the midst of his search, he was bathed in a dazzling light, and then arrived in a strange land whose people and culture differed from his own. And then, time rolled onward. At the old man's request, Tyris held the sandwind flower and offered an awkward smile. Seeing this, the old man nodded in satisfaction. As thanks, he said he would deliver a reward to the public lodge, and then disappeared with little fanfare.

We've defeated the Aberration in the Whispering Cliffs. The aurora winds subsided and the omnistrobe started working again,  which made it clear this was the Aberration that needed to be released. While Feste held Electra's attention, Aeryn was able to conduct the Rite of Release. However, a disturbing figure suddenly apepared—Voldigen, the Dracari Potentate; what's more, Electra revealed her true form, a dracari called Fédra. She had infiltrated the Bapharian Church on Voldigen's orders. She monitored the stimulation of bioflux that came about as a result of Aeryn releasing Aberrations. Voldigen's goal is to devour Aeryn and gain power, and her whereabouts and condition were leaked to him by Fédra.

We were helpless against the onslaught of Voldigen's overwhelming power and were defeated. And just when he had caught Aeryn and was near to consuming her, the Echo Seed I received from Calvain began to shine, and a beautiful voice singing began to flow from it. Voldigen was stricken by this, and he flew away. But before we could collect ourselves, Fédra shapeshifted into a massive form and attacked us. After what was assuredly a life-or-death struggle for us, she disappeared into a deep valley, and we lost all sight of her. The dracari threat has passed. And myself, Feste, Aeryn, and Tyris all managed to survive.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

After he rested up, the young man told us his name: Calvain. He was evidently investigating something in the Soundless City. He seems to have expected the Aberration to be there, but how could he have known that? In any event, he gave me an Echo Seed that he cited as his greatest treasure as thanks for helping him. The moment I took it in hand, the strangest sight flashed through my mind: a young boy swinging a sword in some indeterminate place. Another person stood watching at his side. When I came back to myself, Calvain had already left. I'll have to ask him about what I saw if we run into each other again. In any event, Aeryn finished with banishing the Aberration and we've joined back up. Next stop: the deserts around Salamzahd.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We managed to make it through the checkpoint without issue, and now we can access Salamzahd. One of the best parts of new places is experiencing new cultures, and I for one can't wait.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

We arrived in Salamzahd, but just as we did, an aurora wind swept through and upset the flux flow in the area. This rendered the omnistrobe temporarily unusable, which means we're out of luck using it to track our target for the time being. Aeryn has suggested we go to the Bapharian temple, as we might be able to learn something of use about Aberrations there.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Elenyne also seems to have been concerned about the Aberrations, and was relieved when we told her there was no need to worry. Suddenly, cheers erupted from the square—apparently Charlotte's group was about to begin their performance. Since we promised—and since Aeryn seems bursting at the seams to watch—we'll go and check it out. A little break never hurt anyone.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

I had a strange dream. In the middle of a forest, someone was carrying my body. I could not move, and I could hear crying—a voice calling out over nad over for "Mother." When I oepned my eyes, I saw a bag with a little money in it at my bedside. I then caught a glimpse of Charlotte as she was leaving. Feste seemed to have noticed too, so we pursued her to the entrance of the city. When we caught up to her, she seemed concerned about the armed group that had attacked her. She was afraid of getting the others caught up in the danger, and so had decided to leave by herself. Suddenly, we heard Calvain and Elenyne calling out. As her friend, Elenyne was insistent in wanting to help Charlotte. What's more, with Calvain being a knight of Byrnhald, he was perfectly-suited to protecting Charlotte. On top of that, he had his own reasons for wanting to go into hiding, and he could shelter Charlotte with himself. Convinced, Charlotte left town alongside Calvain. A relief to be sure. Meanwhile, Elenyne explained that she had something she wanted to ask us. Once things have settled down, we should go and hear her out.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

Returning to Salamzahd, an angered Electra accosted Elenyne; apparently she has not been entirely truthful with her on the subject of Jorg. In any event, this seems like the end of the matter for now. Aeryn and Tyris ought to be rested up by now, so we should meet back up with them.

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

A young man has come to the public lodge at the behest of the old man. He explains that the elder man has passed on, and delivers a commemorative Bapharist coin as his thanks. It is exceptionally old, and probably dates from the time of the founders. There is no way to ascertain what truly happened to the old man. The sandwind flower shattered in Tyris' hands and disappeared, as if saying goodbye at the end of a long journey...

◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇　　　　　◇

It has been a long day. So much has happened that lingers in the mind—too much, even. Let's take a rest for now, and we can worry about finding answers afterwards.
